In terms of distribution, except for the high values of SDG 11(Sustainable Cities and Communities) scores in 2010, which are mainly distributed in northeastern China, most of the high values of SDG scores are more likely to be distributed in central and eastern China, both in 2010 and 2020. In 2010, the best performer is SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), the worst performer is SDG 9(Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure). In 2020, the best performer is SDG 12(Responsible Consumption and Production), the worst performer is SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), the regional differences between SDG 6(Clean Water and Sanitation), SDG 11 and SDG 12 shrinking cities are narrowing (Fig. 6

                        ). However, by analysing the changes in the scores of the SDGs, we find that SDG 7, the best performer in 2010, has the most extensive and drastic decline over the decade. SDG 9, the worst performer, has improved considerably over the decade. China's pace of energy restructuring and clean-up has accelerated in recent years, with significant energy savings and emission reductions, but the situation in shrinking cities is not encouraging. The scores for six out of the nine SDGs improved, whereas the scores for the remaining three experienced a decrease over time. These declines, ranked from the most substantial to the least, pertain to SDG 7, SDG 8 (Decent Work and Economic Growth), and SDG 4 (Quality Education). Conversely, the three SDGs that demonstrated the most significant improvements, ranked from the most substantial to the least, were SDG 6, SDG 12, and SDG 9 (Fig. 7
                        ).
